            <p class="destination_p">Mummification Museum:
                Stop by the Mummification Museum to learn more about the ancient Egyptian art of mummification. Find
                more
                about the equipment and artifacts used by ancient embalmers, as well as the complex procedures and
                customs
                involved in preparing the deceased for the afterlife. Highlights include interactive exhibitions delving
                into the secrets of the underworld, funerary masks, and well-preserved mummies.</p>
            <header class="destination_header"> Discover Luxor's East Bank</header>

            <p class="destination_p">Previous Thebes:
                Thebes, the capital of ancient Egypt during the New Kingdom era (16th–11th century BCE), was once known
                as
                Luxor's East Bank. With its beautiful temples honoring the gods and pharaohs, it was a bustling center
                of
                religion, culture, and political power. Egypt tours are on your way to see new experiences in Egypt
                where
                you can learn about the history of the Pharaohs and various monuments</p>
            <p class="destination_p">Position of the Luxor Temple:
                The Avenue of Sphinxes connects Luxor Temple to Karnak Temple in a strategic alignment. With sphinx
                sculptures on either side, this symbolic walkway connected Thebes' spiritual center and functioned as a
                hallowed procession route for religious festivals and festivities.</p>

            <p class="destination_p">Ramses II Obelisks:
                Two enormous red granite obelisks are part of the Luxor Temple; one is still standing, while the other
                is on
                display at the Place de la Concorde in Paris, France. Ramses II ordered these obelisks as a sign of the
                pharaoh's reverence for the deity Amun-Ra and his wish to exalt Egypt's magnificence. Visit Luxor
                through
                various Luxor day tours with Mr Egypt, where they will travel with you.</p>
            <p class="destination_p">Contemporary Archaeological Findings:
                Archaeological finds on Luxor's East Bank are coming to light. The discovery of ancient workshops,
                residential spaces, and a cache of sacred relics during recent digs close to Luxor Temple has offered
                insight into the everyday lives and religious rituals of the people who lived in ancient Thebes. If you
                are
                a fan of visiting classic places, Classical Egypt Tours is your best choice to learn about the country’s
                unparalleled history. The East Bank of Luxor is a thriving center of contemporary Egyptian culture in
                addition to being a focus of ancient history. Discovering vibrant marketplaces, dining at authentic
                eateries, and going to cultural events with art, dance, and music may provide visitors with a deep and
                comprehensive look into modern Egyptian culture</p>
            <p class="destination_p">Luxor's designation as a UNESCO World Heritage Site:
                Recognized for its exceptional global value and cultural significance, Luxor's East Bank and West Bank
                have
                been named UNESCO World Heritage Sites. This esteemed position highlights how crucial it is to protect
                Luxor's rich archeological legacy so that future generations can enjoy and value it.</p>
